  "prompt": "What does \"ride or die\" mean and where did it come from?",
  "response": "\"Ride or die\" is a colloquial expression that refers to a person who is steadfastly loyal and committed, no matter the circumstances or challenges faced. This person supports and stands by someone through thick and thin, akin to a devoted companion who would do anything for their partner or friend. The phrase conveys a deep sense of loyalty and unwavering support.\n\nThe origins of \"ride or die\" are commonly attributed to motorcycle culture and the idea of riding together through life's ups and downs. It gained broader popularity through hip-hop music and culture in the late 20th and early 21st centuries. The phrase was further popularized by artists like DMX and others, who used it to describe loyalty and commitment in relationships and friendships.\n\nOverall, \"ride or die\" has evolved to represent a strong bond and commitment between people, encompassing themes of loyalty, support, and unwavering dedication.",
